Automating Security Groups 
  Declaring Security Groups in a CloudFormation Template
    Here’s a simple example snippet:
    Resources:
      WebServerSecurityGroup:
        Type: AWS::EC2::SecurityGroup
        Properties:
          GroupDescription: Allow HTTP and SSH access
          VpcId: !Ref VPC
          SecurityGroupIngress:
            - IpProtocol: tcp
              FromPort: 22
              ToPort: 22
              CidrIp: 0.0.0.0/0
            - IpProtocol: tcp
              FromPort: 80
              ToPort: 80
              CidrIp: 0.0.0.0/0
          Tags:
            - Key: Name
              Value: WebSG
    This YAML code creates a security group that allows SSH (port 22) and HTTP (port 80) access from any IP address, with tagging for easy identification.
  Creating Reusable and Modular Security Group Templates
    Example parameterized setup:
    Parameters:
      SSHLocation:
        Type: String
        Default: 0.0.0.0/0
        Description: IP address range that can SSH to the EC2 instance
  Linking Security Groups to Resources Programmatically
    Example EC2 attachment:
    Resources:
      EC2Instance:
        Type: AWS::EC2::Instance
        Properties:
          SecurityGroupIds:
            - !Ref WebServerSecurityGroup
  Automating Rules for Ingress and Egress Traffic
    In cloud environments, controlling how data enters and exits your resources is vital to maintaining a secure network. Ingress and egress rules define the traffic allowed into and out of your AWS infrastructure. By automating these rules with AWS CloudFormation, you can enforce security standards consistently across deployments, eliminate manual configuration errors, and scale securely.
    Defining Ingress Rules in CloudFormation Templates
      Example snippet for inbound rules:
      SecurityGroupIngress:
      - IpProtocol: tcp
          FromPort: 443
          ToPort: 443
        CidrIp: 0.0.0.0/0
      - IpProtocol: tcp
          FromPort: 22
          ToPort: 22
      CidrIp: !Ref SSHLocation
    This setup ensures that HTTPS is always accessible, while SSH access is configurable during stack deployment via a parameter.
  Automating Egress Rules to Control Outbound Traffic
    Here’s a sample configuration:
    SecurityGroupEgress:
      - IpProtocol: -1
      CidrIp: 0.0.0.0/0
  Using Parameters and Mappings for Dynamic Rule Management
    Example of a parameterized rule:
    Parameters:
    WebPort:
      Type: Number
      Default: 80
      Description: Web server port

    SecurityGroupIngress:
      - IpProtocol: tcp
      FromPort: !Ref WebPort
      ToPort: !Ref WebPort
      CidrIp: 0.0.0.0/0
    This ensures flexibility while avoiding hardcoded values.
  Implementing Conditionals for Environment-Specific Access
    Example:
    Conditions:
    IsProd: !Equals [ !Ref Environment, "prod" ]

    Resources:
      ProdSSHAccess:
      Type: AWS::EC2::SecurityGroupIngress
      Condition: IsProd
      Properties:
        GroupId: !Ref MySecurityGroup
        IpProtocol: tcp
        FromPort: 22
        ToPort: 22
        CidrIp: 10.0.0.0/16
  Implementing Least Privilege Network Access
    Designing Security Groups with Minimal Permissions
    Example of overly permissive ingress:
      CidrIp: 0.0.0.0/0
      FromPort: 22
      ToPort: 22
    This allows global SSH access—a major risk.
    Least privilege approach:
    CidrIp: 203.0.113.10/32
      FromPort: 22
      ToPort: 22
    This restricts SSH access to a specific admin IP only.
  Using Conditions in Templates to Control Access Dynamically
     Conditions:
      IsProduction: !Equals [ !Ref EnvType, "prod" ]
  This ensures that resources deployed in lower environments don’t accidentally receive production-level access rules.
